<link href="adcp.css" rel="stylesheet"><entry><xh5>sing like a lark • sing like a nightingale</xh5><p> <i>sing like a lark—</i>sing gaily and cheerfully: Amelia came tripping into the drawing room in a white muslin frock ... <u>singing like a lark</u>, and as fresh as a rose.</p><p> <i>sing like a nightingale—</i>sing very beautifully: Holland comes from a musical family, his father played banjo and his mother <u>sings “like a nightingale</u>.”</p><p> <div class="note">Note</div> Neither expression correlates in meaning with the phrase <b>sing like a canary</b>—(U.S. Underworld) turn informer: You don’t think they’d <u>sing like canaries</u>? ... If they thought it would help them, they’d tell on their mothers.</p> </entry>
